# Create new Dataframe called home_tdf for the home teams stats

home_tdf = pd.DataFrame(columns=cols)
home_cols = ['PL_id','season', 'match_week', 'stadium', 'attendance', 'home_team', 
             'result', 'home_score', 'home_shots', 'home_shotsON', 'home_posse',
             'home_passes', 'home_yellows','home_reds']
home_tdf[cols] = df_base[home_cols]

home_tdf.loc[home_tdf['result']=='home','result'] = 'win'
home_tdf.loc[home_tdf['result']=='away','result'] = 'lose'
home_tdf['team_hospitality'] = 'Home'

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • df_base

    There are 3327 matches from the Premier League matches from 2011 to 2019, it has 22 feature as season, match week, stadium, attendance, home_team, away_team and also the scored goals, shots , passes, yellow and red cards for each team (home and Away) in the match, most of features are numeric, but features as season, stadium, home_team, away_team and result are categorical.

  • df_mod

    This dataset has twice the number if rows of the df_base dataset, because every match has split to two rows, each row describe the stats of one oof two teams (Home / Away), but it has less columns. It has 6654 rows, each columns will be described below.

  • Columns:

    1. season: The year of the season. {Categorical}
    2. match_week: The match week number. {Numeric}
    3. stadium: The name of the stadium where the match was played in. {Categorical}
    4. attendance: The number of fans attended the match at the stadium. {Numeric}
    5. team: Name of the team. {Categorical}
    6. result: The result of the match realative to the team (win, lose, tie). {Categorical}
    7. scored: The number of goals to the mentioned team. {Numeric}
    8. shots: The number of shots of the mentioned team. {Numeric}
    9. shots_on: The number of shots on target of the mentioned team. {Numeric}
    10. posse: The percentange of ball possession of the mentrioned team. {Numeric}
    11. passes: The number of passes in the match related to the mentioned team. {Numeric}
    12. yellows: The number of yellow cards to the montioned team. {Numeric}
    13. reds: The number of red cards to the montioned team. {Numeric}
    14. team_hospitality: it Tells that the match is Home or Away to the mentioned team. {Categorical}

In [25]:
def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    order_dic = kwargs['order']
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    
    sb.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color = default_color, order=order_dic[x.name]);


plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10]);
g = sb.PairGrid(data = df_mod, y_vars = ['passes', 'posse'], x_vars = ['team_hospitality', 'result'],
                height = 4, aspect = 1.5);
g.map(boxgrid, order = order_dic);
plt.show();

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

As shown previously, - there is a postive relation between number of shots and the number of scored goals. The winner team has higher probability to get more ball possession in the game. Also for passes and shots, the winning team has high chance to get more number than the losing team.
The teams that plays at home stadium most probably make more number of passes and shots than the other team, also more ball possesion than the away team.
The plot between the attendance and the result (who win the match -Home or Away-) is interesting, it shows that the home team has higher chance to win the match if the attendance in the home team stadium is high, and the away team can win the match when the attendance in the stadium is low.

The differance between the winning and losing teams in all comparison is very small, but the winning team has higher values in ball possession, passes and shots. the same case at home team and away team, The differances between them are very small, but the home team outperforms the other team.
